\paragraph{Main Results}
We evaluate a range of models on OmniGUIRewardBench under three LLM-as-Judge frameworks—\name\ and two widely used baselines, DigiRL and ZeroGUI. **DigiRL and ZeroGUI represent the two most typical LLM-as-a-Judge frameworks for GUI trajectory reward modeling. Since other existing critic frameworks are largely engineering variations of these two methods, we selected them as our primary baselines for comparison. ZeroGUI adopts a classic decision-making approach by directly feeding $N$ states, including screenshots and webpage information, into the model for judgment. In this work, we specifically utilize the final two frames. In contrast, DigiRL employs a sequential verification method that evaluates states one by one to determine if the objective is met, and this process continues until a state satisfies the goal or the trajectory ends in failure.** As reported in Table~\ref{tab:OmniGUIRewardBench_Simple}, we measure accuracy across different platforms, and further include precision and recall to better characterize performance differences among frameworks. Across all tested base models, \name\ consistently achieves the best results in both accuracy and precision compared to the other frameworks. On average, \name\ outperforms DigiRL by 18.8\%, 29.6\%, 16.9\%, and 26.2\% in accuracy, precision, recall and F1-score, respectively, and surpasses ZeroGUI by 7.7\%, 5.1\%, 13.0\%, and 13.4\% on the same metrics.

